Use a MessagePack library that implements at least version 5 of the\n  MessagePack spec, which supports the BIN and EXT types used by Nvim.\n- Use a single-threaded event loop library/pattern.\n- Use a fiber/coroutine library for the language being used for implementing\n  a client. These greatly simplify concurrency and allow the library to\n  expose a blocking API on top of a non-blocking event loop without the\n  complexity that comes with preemptive multitasking.\n- Don't assume anything about the order of responses to RPC requests.\n- Clients should expect requests, which must be handled immediately because\n  Nvim is blocked while waiting for the client response.\n- Clients should expect notifications, but these can be handled \"ASAP\" (rather\n  than immediately) because they won't block Nvim.\n- For C/C++ projects, consider libmpack instead of the msgpack.org library.\n    https://github.com/libmpack/libmpack/\n  libmpack is small (no dependencies, can inline into your C/C++ project) and\n  efficient (no allocations). It also implements msgpack-RPC, the protocol\n  required by Nvim.\n    https://github.com/msgpack-rpc/msgpack-rpc\n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### Neovim External UI Standard Features\n\nSource: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/runtime/doc/dev.txt\n\nRequirements for external UIs interacting with Neovim. UIs must be aware of the API contract, call nvim_set_client_info() upon connection, and handle cursor style and key input conventions (ALT/META, SUPER keys). Backwards compatibility is maintained, but UIs should not break with new optional fields.\n\n```markdown\nExternal UIs should be aware of the |api-contract|. In particular, future\nversions of Nvim may add new items to existing events. The API is strongly\nbackwards-compatible, but clients must not break if new (optional) fields are\nadded to existing events.\n\nStandard Features ~\n\nExternal UIs are expected to implement these common features:\n\n- Call |nvim_set_client_info()| after connecting, so users and\n  plugins can detect the UI by handling the |ChanInfo| event. This avoids the need for\n  special variables and UI-specific config files (gvimrc, macvimrc, …).\n- Cursor style (shape, color) should conform to the 'guicursor' properties\n  delivered with the mode_info_set UI event.\n- Send the ALT/META (\"Option\" on macOS) key as a |<M-| chord.\n- Send the \"super\" key (Windows key, Apple key) as a |<D-| chord.\n```\n\n--------------------------------\n\n### External UI Requirements\n\nSource: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/master/runtime/doc/dev.txt\n\nRequirements and standard features for external UIs interacting with the Neovim API.\n\n```APIDOC\n## External UI Awareness\n\n### Description\nExternal UIs must be aware of the API contract and handle potential additions to existing events gracefully, ensuring backward compatibility.\n\n### Standard Features\n- Call `nvim_set_client_info()` after connecting for UI detection.\n- Conform cursor style (shape, color) to `guicursor` properties from `mode_info_set` event.\n- Send ALT/META keys as `|<M-|` chords.\n- Send 'super' keys (Windows/Apple) as `|<D-|` chords.\n```\n\n### Introduction\n\nSource: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/wiki/Google-Summer-of-Code\n\nNeovim is a text editor based on Vim. One of the main project goals is to encourage hacking and collaboration. The Neovim source has roots going back to 1987, meaning older libraries were not available at that time. The codebase can be made easier to maintain and understand by using modern libraries. Project ideas that heavily involve \"internals\" will generally be more difficult than those adding new features, but working with complex parts can provide valuable learning feedback for writing simpler, more maintainable code.\n","exit":0,"description":"Get neovim documentation overview","truncated":false},"title":"Get neovim documentation overview","time":{"start":1776634699642,"end":1776634699651}},"id":"